WEBVTT

00:01.125 --> 00:03.083
BYRON:
<i>Previously on</i> Black Cake...

00:03.083 --> 00:06.083
ELEANOR [on recording]:
<i>Forgive me for keeping so many secrets.</i>

00:06.083 --> 00:07.292
BENNY:
<i>The truth is,</i>

00:07.292 --> 00:09.208
learning that your perfect mother
went through some shit

00:09.208 --> 00:11.375
is kind of comforting
when you spent your entire life

00:11.375 --> 00:13.542
feeling like you could
<i>never</i> live up to her standards.

00:13.542 --> 00:17.500
Eight years ago, on Thanksgiving,
was the last time I saw my family.

00:17.500 --> 00:20.917
DALE: Marc, next week,
the board will formally announce you

00:20.917 --> 00:21.917
as the new director.

00:21.917 --> 00:24.500
Byron, you will be reporting to Marc.

00:24.500 --> 00:28.083
ELEANOR [on recording]: <i>B and B,
this is how I really became your ma.</i>

00:28.083 --> 00:29.792
DELROY:
Which school did you go to in Maryville?

00:29.792 --> 00:31.417
My aunt's a teacher over at Stanton.

00:31.417 --> 00:32.750
That's where I went.

00:32.750 --> 00:34.292
[chuckles]
I didn't realize it was co-ed.

00:34.292 --> 00:35.958
Why you lying?

00:35.958 --> 00:38.250
What aren't you telling us, Coventina?

00:38.250 --> 00:40.917
Oh, stop trying to pawn
that boy off on her, Edwina!

00:41.375 --> 00:42.417
ELLY:
<i>To Scotland!</i>

00:42.417 --> 00:43.458
[cups clink]

00:44.083 --> 00:46.250
[thudding]

00:46.250 --> 00:47.625
[people screaming]

00:49.333 --> 00:51.375
Elly!

00:52.083 --> 00:55.208
ELEANOR:
<i>Coventina Brown was now officially dead.</i>

00:56.000 --> 00:57.000
BEATRICE:
Eleanor?

00:57.542 --> 00:58.875
Don't you know your own name?

00:58.875 --> 01:01.208
BOSS:
You're afraid to tell your story
because you are lying.

01:01.208 --> 01:02.292
You're running from something.

01:02.292 --> 01:04.375
I'm so sorry,
I never meant to cause any trouble.

01:04.375 --> 01:06.125
I'll see myself out.
- It's gonna be okay.

01:07.125 --> 01:08.833
COVEY:
No. Please stop.

01:08.833 --> 01:09.875
[thuds]
[gasping]

01:09.875 --> 01:10.917
ELEANOR:
<i>You grow up thinking</i>

01:10.917 --> 01:13.458
<i>that when someone does
something terrible to you,</i>

01:13.458 --> 01:15.708
<i>you will react, you will fight back.</i>

01:16.583 --> 01:18.458
<i>London wasn't exactly safe,</i>

01:18.875 --> 01:20.792
<i>but there he was,</i>

01:20.792 --> 01:23.625
<i>my past, right in front of me.</i>

01:24.833 --> 01:26.292
<i>I had to ask myself,</i>

01:26.833 --> 01:29.083
<i>did I want to be seen?</i>

01:32.917 --> 01:38.042
[crowd chanting indistinctly]

01:40.250 --> 01:43.458
CROWD [chanting]:
We will! We will! We will...

01:44.083 --> 01:47.083
♪ intense music playing ♪

01:51.708 --> 01:53.708
♪

02:05.417 --> 02:08.083
Down with the slumlords!
We are British just like you!

02:08.750 --> 02:11.792
♪ intense music continues playing ♪

02:11.792 --> 02:13.042
Fair housing now!

02:15.333 --> 02:17.708
[indistinct chanting continues]

02:17.708 --> 02:19.458
[brakes squealing]
[horn blares]

02:28.750 --> 02:30.042
My God, Covey!

02:31.583 --> 02:32.583
Don't call me that.

02:33.750 --> 02:35.750
♪

02:41.792 --> 02:43.833
I wanted to make Scotland work.

02:45.958 --> 02:49.042
I thought I could make
a new life for myself there, but--

02:53.750 --> 02:58.125
But then my-- my coworkers started
to suspect I was lying about who I was,

02:58.125 --> 03:02.042
so I left
before they could ask any more questions.

03:02.583 --> 03:04.583
All this time, I thought I'd lost you.

03:06.583 --> 03:08.333
I still can't believe you're really here.

03:10.125 --> 03:12.042
You have no idea how good it feels

03:12.792 --> 03:15.333
to be able to talk to someone
who knows the real me.

03:18.417 --> 03:20.625
I was afraid you'd forgotten about me.

03:20.625 --> 03:21.625
Never.

03:30.500 --> 03:33.000
When I read about the accident,
I tried to move on,

03:34.167 --> 03:35.000
but,

03:35.667 --> 03:36.750
no one else compared.

03:38.875 --> 03:40.542
Turns out, you're my one and only.

03:45.083 --> 03:45.917
But,

03:46.792 --> 03:48.833
maybe it was silly to hold onto that.

03:50.625 --> 03:51.833
Why would you say that?

03:53.708 --> 03:55.583
I thought maybe
you had found someone else.

03:56.708 --> 03:57.708
Well, have you?

03:59.833 --> 04:01.208
Have you thought of me?

04:04.042 --> 04:04.958
Gibbs,

04:06.042 --> 04:08.000
thinking of you has been my escape.

04:09.250 --> 04:11.042
A reminder of who I was.

04:13.083 --> 04:14.083
Who I am.

04:15.917 --> 04:17.667
You're my one and only.

04:19.708 --> 04:20.917
You always will be.

04:21.833 --> 04:24.833
♪

04:32.542 --> 04:34.500
I do have a favor to ask, though.

04:36.833 --> 04:38.042
Can we take it slow?

04:39.333 --> 04:40.250
Of course.

04:41.958 --> 04:42.958
As slow as you like.

04:44.042 --> 04:47.625
ELEANOR: <i>How could I tell Gibbs
what had happened to me in Scotland?</i>

04:48.875 --> 04:52.000
<i>I didn't want him
to think of me any differently.</i>

04:53.750 --> 04:58.000
<i>And I had a feeling
that he was keeping secrets from me too.</i>

04:59.000 --> 05:00.208
[projector whirring]

05:00.208 --> 05:02.875
ELEANOR:
<i>But we buried all of that,</i>

05:03.375 --> 05:05.667
<i>and we started living again.</i>

05:05.667 --> 05:07.167
[ <i>Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid</i>
playing on screen]

05:07.167 --> 05:08.875
BUTCH: <i>Then you jump first.</i>
SUNDANCE: <i>No, I said.</i>

05:08.875 --> 05:11.000
BUTCH: <i>What's the matter with you?</i>
SUNDANCE: <i>I can't swim!</i>

05:11.000 --> 05:14.417
BUTCH: <i>Why you crazy?
The fall will probably kill you.</i>

05:15.792 --> 05:17.792
[thunder rumbling]

05:20.458 --> 05:23.917
Remember when we used to beg for rain
to save us from the heat?

05:23.917 --> 05:25.167
Now it's just a nuisance.

05:28.250 --> 05:29.583
Speaking of those days,

05:30.292 --> 05:31.375
have you heard from Bunny?

05:32.792 --> 05:33.625
No.

05:34.208 --> 05:35.750
I only went back there once,

05:36.708 --> 05:39.292
after the accident,
when I had to settle my parent's estate.

05:40.667 --> 05:41.875
I wish I could've met them.

05:43.125 --> 05:44.125
Me too.

05:45.958 --> 05:48.000
But I didn't want
to see anyone from before.

05:48.000 --> 05:49.000
Why not?

05:50.333 --> 05:51.333
Too many memories.

05:52.500 --> 05:53.708
Our memories.

05:56.875 --> 06:02.667
But I did hear that the police arrested
someone named Short Stack or Short Shirt,

06:02.667 --> 06:04.000
something like that.

06:04.000 --> 06:05.708
There wasn't much evidence, though, so,

06:06.792 --> 06:08.042
case is still open.

06:09.417 --> 06:10.458
EDWINA:
Coventina?

06:12.542 --> 06:13.792
I can't believe it!

06:14.333 --> 06:15.333
Edwina!

06:15.333 --> 06:17.125
We all thought you were dead!

06:17.125 --> 06:19.375
We-- We read about the train crash.

06:19.375 --> 06:21.583
You were listed as one of the victims.

06:21.583 --> 06:22.750
I-I know, I--

06:23.875 --> 06:25.625
It was a mistake.
- Where is Elly?

06:26.167 --> 06:28.250
I thought for sure,
she would've written by now.

06:28.250 --> 06:29.292
I'm sorry.

06:30.542 --> 06:33.375
♪ dramatic music playing ♪

06:35.625 --> 06:38.625
[Covey panting]

06:44.667 --> 06:45.583
Covey?

06:48.292 --> 06:49.958
Hey, just breathe.

06:51.042 --> 06:52.250
[heavy breaths]

06:53.875 --> 06:55.292
We can't do this.

06:55.958 --> 06:56.958
What? Do what?

06:57.917 --> 06:59.167
Be together.

06:59.167 --> 07:00.708
You saw what just happened.

07:01.208 --> 07:03.042
I stole someone's identity.

07:03.792 --> 07:06.083
I buried Coventina to be Eleanor,

07:06.667 --> 07:08.375
which means that for the rest of my life,

07:08.375 --> 07:10.167
I'm gonna keep looking over my shoulder,

07:10.708 --> 07:12.583
running from people like Edwina.

07:12.583 --> 07:14.875
[thunder rumbling]

07:14.875 --> 07:17.000
You don't want to
live a life of secrets.

07:18.292 --> 07:19.458
We all have secrets.

07:20.625 --> 07:21.625
Not like mine.

07:23.958 --> 07:26.083
I don't want to put you in any danger.

07:26.667 --> 07:29.292
And as long as I stay in London,
I'll never have peace.

07:30.542 --> 07:31.958
We'll never have peace.

07:32.458 --> 07:33.458
Then let's leave.

07:34.458 --> 07:36.833
I have some money put away
from my parents.

07:36.833 --> 07:38.750
We'll jump on the next plane out of here.

07:39.375 --> 07:42.125
Start someplace fresh. Someplace far away.

07:42.125 --> 07:43.583
And we'll never look back again.

07:43.583 --> 07:45.333
And have you give up your entire life?

07:45.333 --> 07:48.542
I can't go back to Jamaica.
Little Man's brothers think I'm dead.

07:48.542 --> 07:49.875
We may not be able to go back,

07:50.458 --> 07:51.875
but we can go forward.

07:52.917 --> 07:53.750
Together.

07:55.042 --> 07:58.042
♪

07:59.625 --> 08:01.583
Marry me, Covey.

08:02.000 --> 08:04.292
And I promise
you'll never carry your secrets alone.

08:06.333 --> 08:08.625
[laughs, sniffles]
Are you crazy?

08:08.625 --> 08:09.458
Marry me.

08:10.292 --> 08:13.042
And I promise to buy you a ring
as soon as we get where we're going.

08:13.458 --> 08:14.375
[Covey sniffles]

08:15.125 --> 08:16.125
[laughs, sniffles]

08:18.458 --> 08:19.792
But where will we go?
[inhales sharply]

08:20.250 --> 08:21.625
Marry me, and I'll tell you.

08:25.542 --> 08:28.542
<i>♪ My Baby Just Cares For Me</i>
by Nina Simone playing ♪

08:30.833 --> 08:34.083
<i>♪ My baby don't care for shows ♪</i>

08:34.875 --> 08:38.542
<i>♪ My baby don't care for clothes ♪</i>

08:39.833 --> 08:42.875
<i>♪ My baby just cares for me... ♪</i>

08:46.917 --> 08:50.708
ELEANOR:
<i>Back then, it was easier to disappear.</i>

08:52.292 --> 08:53.292
<i>Back then,</i>

08:54.500 --> 08:57.042
<i>you could open a new bank account,</i>

08:57.625 --> 09:01.417
<i>or get a driver's license
with just part of your birth name.</i>

09:02.875 --> 09:06.125
<i>♪ Liz Taylor is not his style ♪</i>

09:06.833 --> 09:10.333
<i>♪ And even Lana Turner's smile... ♪</i>

09:11.042 --> 09:13.292
Promise me that
when we have a family of our own,

09:13.917 --> 09:15.125
we'll start fresh.

09:16.083 --> 09:18.792
I want this to be
the only wedding night we remember.

09:20.167 --> 09:21.583
We'll never speak of it again.

09:23.292 --> 09:27.667
ELEANOR:
<i>Back then, "Gibbs" Gilbert Bennett Grant</i>

09:29.417 --> 09:33.875
<i>cut all ties with his past
to be with the woman he loved.</i>

09:35.583 --> 09:37.292
Happy anniversary, Bert.

09:37.833 --> 09:39.250
ELEANOR:
<i>Yes, B and B,</i>

09:40.042 --> 09:43.083
<i>Gibbs, my one and only...</i>

09:43.083 --> 09:45.167
[both laughing]

09:45.167 --> 09:47.500
ELEANOR:
<i>...is your father, Bert.</i>

09:47.500 --> 09:48.792
Take this, son.

09:49.833 --> 09:51.625
Let the old folks show you how it's done.

09:51.625 --> 09:54.458
Wait, wait, Bert, before you start,

09:54.458 --> 09:56.917
I want to make a toast.

09:59.167 --> 10:03.375
Congratulations, Byron,
on getting your dream job.

10:03.958 --> 10:06.458
You've known
you wanted to be an ocean scientist

10:06.458 --> 10:09.042
ever since you were six years old,

10:09.958 --> 10:12.750
and you've overcome so much to get here.

10:14.208 --> 10:15.875
We're so proud of you.

10:15.875 --> 10:18.417
And... to my Benedetta,

10:18.417 --> 10:20.125
you have so many talents:

10:20.958 --> 10:24.000
your music, your painting, your cooking.

10:24.000 --> 10:26.083
I love how passionate you are,

10:26.083 --> 10:28.042
and I hope that
culinary school brings you

10:28.042 --> 10:30.792
all the success and joy that you seek.

10:30.792 --> 10:31.792
ELEANOR:
Mm-hmm.

10:31.792 --> 10:32.917
Thanks, Dad.

10:33.375 --> 10:34.208
BYRON:
Amen.

10:36.708 --> 10:38.833
[glasses clink]
[Eleanor chuckles]

10:39.208 --> 10:42.042
Now, I hope
one day in the not-too-distant future,

10:42.042 --> 10:45.042
we'll be toasting to our in-laws.

10:45.042 --> 10:47.125
Speaking of,

10:47.625 --> 10:51.208
Byron has made some progress
in that department.

10:51.708 --> 10:53.042
Who is she, Byron?

10:53.042 --> 10:54.167
Who is she?

10:54.167 --> 10:57.417
If you must know, her name is Lynette.

10:57.417 --> 11:01.667
And we met when I was being interviewed
for that <i>Trailblazers</i> documentary.

11:02.292 --> 11:05.500
<i>Her</i> documentary. She's a director, Ma.

11:05.500 --> 11:09.000
And she is <i>really</i>
making a name for herself in that world.

11:09.000 --> 11:10.500
Well, I can't wait to meet her.

11:10.500 --> 11:11.417
[Eleanor chuckles]

11:11.417 --> 11:15.000
And... what about you, hm?

11:15.000 --> 11:18.125
Is there a young man
I should be giving a <i>stern</i> talking to?

11:19.750 --> 11:23.833
I thought you were gonna
school us on charades, old man. Hm?

11:23.833 --> 11:25.958
All right, you want some schooling?

11:25.958 --> 11:28.875
[all laughing]

11:30.583 --> 11:33.625
Ahh!
[chuckles, clears throat]

11:36.292 --> 11:37.958
Woosh!

11:37.958 --> 11:39.208
Pelican.

11:39.208 --> 11:41.500
Woooosh!
[Benny and Byron laughing]

11:41.500 --> 11:42.500
Parasail!

11:42.500 --> 11:43.625
[timer buzzing]
- That's time.

11:43.625 --> 11:45.375
It was tidal wave!

11:45.917 --> 11:48.042
I thought
that would be easy for you, Covey.

11:49.750 --> 11:52.750
BENNY: Woosh!
[Benny and Byron laughing]

11:52.750 --> 11:55.750
♪ tense music playing ♪

11:56.917 --> 11:58.917
[Benny and Byron continue laughing]

12:00.917 --> 12:02.958
Um... I'm sorry, I--

12:05.208 --> 12:06.208
I need to lie down.

12:13.042 --> 12:13.875
[door closes]

12:16.208 --> 12:17.042
[Bert sighs]

12:20.167 --> 12:21.167
I'm sorry.

12:22.708 --> 12:25.125
It just... slipped out.

12:25.125 --> 12:25.958
No.

12:26.708 --> 12:27.708
I'm sorry.

12:28.458 --> 12:30.292
[deep breath]

12:30.292 --> 12:33.083
It's just hearing that name
brought everything back up again.

12:33.667 --> 12:35.167
[deep breath]

12:35.167 --> 12:37.875
And it reminded me
how much we've kept from the kids.

12:38.583 --> 12:39.417
Well,

12:40.500 --> 12:43.083
maybe it's time
we finally tell them the truth.

12:45.500 --> 12:47.042
All these secrets,

12:49.458 --> 12:51.917
they're a burden, Eleanor.

12:52.458 --> 12:54.792
Look what they've done to you, hm?

12:54.792 --> 12:56.792
It's been so long.

12:58.333 --> 12:59.375
Hm.

12:59.375 --> 13:00.875
Who we running from now, huh?

13:02.000 --> 13:03.417
We've waited too long.

13:04.583 --> 13:06.583
Now what good would it do
to tell them now?

13:06.583 --> 13:10.125
I'm thinking about
what it will do for <i>you,</i> my love.

13:12.792 --> 13:13.792
I know.

13:17.417 --> 13:19.167
And I adore you for it.

13:20.125 --> 13:21.083
[heavy breath]

13:21.500 --> 13:23.292
But I can't think about myself.

13:24.750 --> 13:25.750
Not now.

13:25.750 --> 13:28.083
Telling them
won't change anything for them

13:28.083 --> 13:29.833
except how they see us.

13:30.875 --> 13:33.542
So why go through
all that pain and heartache?

13:34.375 --> 13:36.750
What happens if they resent us?

13:37.250 --> 13:38.708
What if they can't forgive us?

13:39.583 --> 13:41.125
Do you really think that would happen?

13:42.500 --> 13:44.167
I walked away from my father,

13:45.625 --> 13:47.917
and my mother walked away from me.

13:50.583 --> 13:54.292
Betrayal... is a powerful thing.

13:54.292 --> 13:55.250
Hm.

13:55.875 --> 14:00.625
And I'd rather suffer in silence
than risk losing our children.

14:01.333 --> 14:02.333
[door opens]

14:03.708 --> 14:04.833
You okay, Ma?

14:04.833 --> 14:05.833
Oh.

14:07.833 --> 14:08.833
Yes, honey.

14:10.542 --> 14:12.542
She just needs to rest.
ELEANOR: Mm.

14:13.208 --> 14:14.042
[Bert chuckles]

14:17.042 --> 14:17.875
BERT: Hm.

14:19.125 --> 14:19.958
ELEANOR: Hm.

14:20.125 --> 14:23.250
[Bert humming]

14:26.542 --> 14:27.625
I love you.

14:28.958 --> 14:29.958
You too.

14:35.125 --> 14:36.125
Come on.

14:37.542 --> 14:40.917
ELEANOR: <i>I wish now
that I had listened to your father.</i>

14:41.917 --> 14:45.167
<i>Maybe if I had
shared my secrets, Benny,</i>

14:46.167 --> 14:47.625
<i>it could have brought us closer.</i>

14:48.292 --> 14:49.292
<i>Maybe</i>

14:50.000 --> 14:53.333
<i>it could have kept you
from running away that Thanksgiving.</i>

14:58.708 --> 15:00.917
I can't believe
she didn't tell Dad about Scotland.

15:01.583 --> 15:03.000
The saddest part is,

15:04.333 --> 15:05.875
I think Dad would've wanted to know.

15:07.792 --> 15:10.167
Did he tell you any of this?

15:10.167 --> 15:11.833
No. No.

15:12.458 --> 15:16.292
Truest thing about... Bert Bennett

15:16.292 --> 15:18.583
was his character, not his name.

15:20.083 --> 15:21.292
You wanna keep listening?

15:21.292 --> 15:23.375
Mm, I can stay as long as you like.

15:23.375 --> 15:25.042
No. Thank you.

15:26.958 --> 15:27.792
I need a break.

15:27.792 --> 15:30.083
MR. MITCH:
[chuckles] I thought you might.

15:30.833 --> 15:33.042
Call me when you're ready to dive back in.

15:33.042 --> 15:34.042
You know the drill.

15:34.750 --> 15:37.625
And, uh... take as long as you need, hm?

15:42.917 --> 15:46.667
Do you really think
Dad would've wanted to know <i>everything</i>

15:47.542 --> 15:48.750
that Mom went through?

15:49.250 --> 15:50.083
I do.

15:51.500 --> 15:52.917
Might've helped her in some way.

15:53.583 --> 15:54.500
Him too.

15:55.000 --> 15:57.125
She must have felt so alone.

16:01.667 --> 16:04.375
How could Ma have had Bunny in her life,

16:05.208 --> 16:08.167
how could she have
gone through so much with her,

16:08.167 --> 16:10.542
and let Dad be so judgmental with me?

16:12.542 --> 16:14.333
Hey. Look...

16:14.958 --> 16:16.000
That, uh...

16:18.417 --> 16:21.917
Thanksgiving was horrible. For all of us.

16:22.750 --> 16:24.583
But why didn't you come back?

16:25.542 --> 16:27.792
All these years?

16:27.792 --> 16:28.917
I reached out.

16:29.417 --> 16:30.833
You never answered me.

16:30.833 --> 16:32.333
What was I gonna come back to?

16:33.958 --> 16:35.042
More judgment?

16:35.042 --> 16:36.208
You felt judged by me?

16:36.208 --> 16:37.208
Yes!

16:38.458 --> 16:39.583
By all of you.

16:40.417 --> 16:44.125
♪ somber music playing ♪

16:47.208 --> 16:48.500
What about when Dad died?

16:50.875 --> 16:52.792
You said you'd come to the funeral.

16:52.792 --> 16:55.250
[voice breaks] We waited for you, Benny--
- I wanted to be there.

16:57.917 --> 16:59.583
But--
- But what?

17:02.417 --> 17:04.292
Come on, you can tell me, Ben.

17:12.708 --> 17:14.458
You wouldn't understand.

17:15.917 --> 17:17.917
Wait, where are you going?
I just want to talk--

17:17.917 --> 17:19.083
Please.

17:19.083 --> 17:21.000
Just give me some space, okay?

17:22.375 --> 17:23.375
I gotta go.

17:27.042 --> 17:28.875
[front door opens, shuts]

17:29.250 --> 17:31.625
[indistinct chatter]
[traffic noise, cars honking]

17:45.833 --> 17:47.083
Surprise.

17:47.083 --> 17:48.667
What are you doing here?

17:48.667 --> 17:51.042
Well, it's... been a while,

17:51.042 --> 17:55.500
so I thought I'd drop by
and see if everything was okay.

17:56.000 --> 17:57.000
It's not, actually.

17:58.792 --> 17:59.792
My mom died.

17:59.792 --> 18:01.958
Oh, God. Benny, that's awful.

18:04.500 --> 18:06.750
I did come bearing some news
that might cheer you up.

18:08.833 --> 18:10.458
I think you could use a little

18:11.833 --> 18:13.250
good news right about now.

18:14.292 --> 18:15.292
Couldn't you?

18:18.417 --> 18:21.417
<i>♪ Sandman</i> by Tameca Jones playing ♪

18:24.083 --> 18:25.708
[doorbell rings]

18:28.750 --> 18:30.542
Hey. Welcome home.

18:33.083 --> 18:33.917
[dog barks]

18:35.458 --> 18:37.458
I'm sorry. My flight was delayed.

18:39.708 --> 18:43.917
So how bad
was the latest message from beyond?

18:44.833 --> 18:46.375
Let's open the beers first.

18:48.167 --> 18:52.417
So... you know that sculpture we made,

18:53.417 --> 18:55.292
the one we said we would never sell?

18:58.250 --> 18:59.667
Well, Helena called.

19:01.250 --> 19:02.375
She has a buyer.

19:03.458 --> 19:07.375
It's a substantial offer,
and I think we ought to consider it.

19:07.375 --> 19:11.917
I don't think I want that piece
displayed in someone's house, Steve.

19:12.792 --> 19:14.250
I mean, it's personal.

19:14.250 --> 19:15.250
Look.

19:18.042 --> 19:19.042
It's good money.

19:20.958 --> 19:23.417
You could open that café
you're always going on about.

19:24.208 --> 19:25.417
LYNETTE:
<i>Must be really hard on Benny.</i>

19:27.458 --> 19:29.042
Maybe harder, in some ways.

19:30.583 --> 19:31.958
What makes you say that?

19:33.292 --> 19:36.625
It's been <i>eight years</i>
since she's been back home,

19:37.792 --> 19:38.625
and...

19:39.875 --> 19:41.750
this is what's waiting for her?

19:43.208 --> 19:47.167
<i>I mean, death is disruptive</i>

19:48.375 --> 19:49.708
<i>and painful,</i>

19:52.083 --> 19:54.208
but it's also a natural part of life.

19:56.167 --> 19:58.500
What Eleanor's done here isn't.

20:00.875 --> 20:02.250
Let me be here for you.

20:06.042 --> 20:07.417
You just tell me what you need.

20:08.042 --> 20:09.042
LYNETTE:
<i>If it were me,</i>

20:10.417 --> 20:11.833
<i>I'd feel manipulated.</i>

20:12.167 --> 20:18.042
<i>♪ ...can make me hope ♪</i>

20:19.542 --> 20:22.792
<i>♪ I'm drowning inside... ♪</i>

20:24.250 --> 20:26.750
I don't think
I could do that to my children.

20:28.417 --> 20:29.875
She did the best she could.

20:29.875 --> 20:30.875
I know.

20:31.542 --> 20:32.542
Of course, she did.

20:34.083 --> 20:36.625
And she's also managed
to bring you and Benny back together,

20:36.625 --> 20:40.458
which, let me tell you,
I <i>never</i> thought would happen.

20:43.625 --> 20:46.667
<i>♪ It's since you've been gone ♪</i>

20:47.000 --> 20:49.958
I can always count on you, can't I?

20:53.833 --> 20:56.833
♪

21:04.792 --> 21:07.708
<i>♪ If my pillow could talk ♪</i>

21:07.708 --> 21:11.667
<i>♪ It'd cry out his name ♪</i>

21:12.750 --> 21:15.792
<i>♪ Oh-oh-oh, cry out ♪</i>

21:18.708 --> 21:23.000
<i>♪ Cry out his name ♪</i>

21:26.083 --> 21:27.958
- I've missed you.
- Mm.

21:31.417 --> 21:32.792
How'd it go at work?

21:36.708 --> 21:38.708
You asking because you want to know,

21:40.083 --> 21:41.625
or because you already know?

21:43.792 --> 21:45.292
I follow Marc on Twitter.

21:46.792 --> 21:47.917
Why? [sighs]

21:48.417 --> 21:49.667
I'm a masochist.

21:49.667 --> 21:52.250
Why didn't you tell me
they promoted him over you?

21:53.458 --> 21:54.667
'Cause it isn't that deep.

21:56.208 --> 21:58.583
People don't always get
the jobs they want,

21:58.583 --> 22:00.458
it's the nature of competition.

22:00.458 --> 22:03.375
If this was a competition,
you'd have won.

22:03.375 --> 22:06.792
This is <i>purely</i> about them not wanting
to put you in a position of power.

22:06.792 --> 22:09.542
Instead, they'd rather
praise Marc fucking Bishop

22:09.542 --> 22:11.542
and flog you as their mascot!

22:12.750 --> 22:14.167
I'm not a mascot, Lynette.

22:15.042 --> 22:17.292
You know how hard I've worked.

22:17.292 --> 22:20.750
This is the only institute
that prioritizes my kind of research.

22:20.750 --> 22:23.833
And you want me to throw that away
by playing the race card?

22:24.333 --> 22:26.042
I want you to get angry.

22:26.042 --> 22:28.417
Because this <i>is</i> about race.

22:28.417 --> 22:30.375
Because your mother overcame so much

22:30.375 --> 22:32.583
and your father was a civil rights lawyer.

22:32.583 --> 22:34.292
And you can't even summon the courage

22:34.292 --> 22:36.750
to fight what is clearly
workplace discrimination?

22:36.750 --> 22:38.542
Don't use my parents to shame me.

22:39.292 --> 22:40.625
I'm sorry. That's not what I meant.

22:40.625 --> 22:41.917
Except, that is what you meant.

22:43.667 --> 22:46.208
I-It's not <i>only</i> what I meant.

22:47.458 --> 22:50.833
You're an extraordinary scientist,

22:50.833 --> 22:54.792
and you deserve to be recognized
and respected for what you do.

22:55.750 --> 22:57.417
But you know
they will never give you that.

22:57.917 --> 22:59.500
And rather than do something about it,

22:59.500 --> 23:01.917
it seems like you're happy
to just lie down and take it.

23:03.167 --> 23:05.333
I don't care
how it seems to you, Lynette.

23:06.292 --> 23:07.833
No. You know what?

23:07.833 --> 23:10.292
♪ solemn music playing ♪

23:12.208 --> 23:13.250
[deep breath]

23:14.125 --> 23:15.125
Can you just go?

23:16.500 --> 23:17.333
Please.

23:17.542 --> 23:21.958
♪

23:35.417 --> 23:36.583
[Benny chuckles]

23:38.000 --> 23:38.833
[Joanie chuckles]

23:39.500 --> 23:42.250
Ooh, we should probably put this out.

23:42.250 --> 23:45.833
We can't turn up
to Sunday dinner baked again. [chuckles]

23:45.833 --> 23:50.500
Uh... or we could stay here

23:50.500 --> 23:53.208
and interrogate orgasmic discourse.

23:53.208 --> 23:55.000
- Mm-mm.
- Mmm.

23:55.000 --> 23:55.958
[Joanie chuckles]

24:00.375 --> 24:02.500
JOANIE: Hm.
[Benny chuckles]

24:05.042 --> 24:07.708
[both coughing, laughing]

24:10.167 --> 24:14.417
Or, if you'd rather,
we could skip dinner at my mom's,

24:15.583 --> 24:17.625
we could go down to the OC,

24:18.333 --> 24:19.708
go see your parents?

24:20.875 --> 24:22.250
It'd be nice to finally meet them.

24:24.542 --> 24:27.292
I haven't... told them about us.

24:30.417 --> 24:31.625
About me.

24:33.208 --> 24:34.042
[Joanie gasps]

24:34.917 --> 24:36.833
I mean, they're great.

24:36.833 --> 24:39.083
Like, on the right side
of history and everything.

24:39.083 --> 24:39.917
It's just--

24:40.583 --> 24:42.250
They can be very critical.

24:43.250 --> 24:44.250
I get it.

24:45.208 --> 24:47.125
My family needed a minute
when I came out.

24:48.417 --> 24:49.250
Yeah.

24:50.625 --> 24:52.125
It's more complicated.

24:54.000 --> 24:55.417
[sighs] See, my parents,

24:55.417 --> 24:56.583
they have an expectation

24:56.583 --> 24:59.792
of what their first-generation
American daughter should be,

24:59.792 --> 25:02.792
and... I will never be that.

25:05.875 --> 25:06.875
Benny,

25:09.167 --> 25:12.333
I have worked really hard
to live my truth,

25:14.042 --> 25:17.125
and I don't wanna push you to
do something you're not ready to do, but,

25:19.250 --> 25:21.250
I'm not interested in hiding again.

25:21.250 --> 25:25.208
No, Jo-- Joanie, I wo--
I would never want you to think that.

25:25.208 --> 25:26.542
That is not what I'm doing.

25:32.792 --> 25:34.875
I know my parents would love to meet you.

25:40.500 --> 25:43.083
<i>♪ Thanks to You</i> by Ronnie Walker playing ♪

25:43.083 --> 25:44.083
[door bell ringing]

25:46.458 --> 25:49.417
Hey! Look at you!

25:49.417 --> 25:50.792
I clean up nice, right?

25:50.792 --> 25:51.792
BENNY:
Very nice.

25:52.958 --> 25:55.042
<i>♪ Sunrise ♪</i>

25:57.917 --> 25:58.917
Thank you.

26:01.042 --> 26:03.417
<i>♪ Sunset ♪</i>

26:04.042 --> 26:04.958
[Joanie chuckles]

26:04.958 --> 26:07.208
<i>♪ For now... ♪</i>

26:07.208 --> 26:08.792
BENNY:
Way to ease her in, fam.

26:10.125 --> 26:11.375
Um...

26:11.375 --> 26:13.417
Hi. I'm Joanie.

26:13.417 --> 26:14.708
Hi. Byron.

26:15.500 --> 26:17.375
Lynette. Happy Thanksgiving.

26:17.375 --> 26:18.583
Happy Thanksgiving.

26:19.083 --> 26:20.792
I'm Eleanor.

26:20.792 --> 26:23.833
It's so nice to meet you.

26:23.833 --> 26:26.333
Uh, this is my husband, Bert.

26:26.333 --> 26:29.167
[chuckles] Welcome to our home.

26:29.958 --> 26:31.417
I hope you're hungry.

26:31.417 --> 26:33.250
We've been exiled
from the kitchen for hours,

26:33.250 --> 26:34.875
so it must be nearly time to eat.

26:34.875 --> 26:36.708
Oh, okay.
[laughter]

26:36.708 --> 26:37.625
So.

26:38.208 --> 26:39.042
Come.

26:41.208 --> 26:44.500
<i>♪ ...so much happiness ♪</i>

26:47.250 --> 26:50.375
My son listens to the sea for a living.

26:50.375 --> 26:51.667
Can you imagine?
[laughter]

26:51.667 --> 26:53.208
It's actually a job!

26:53.958 --> 26:55.458
It's pretty amazing.

26:56.250 --> 26:59.542
Almost as amazing as these yams, Benny.

27:00.250 --> 27:02.625
Only one more year
of culinary school, Benedetta.

27:02.625 --> 27:05.000
Have you started applying
for apprenticeships yet?

27:06.792 --> 27:07.625
No.

27:08.333 --> 27:09.167
I haven't.

27:10.750 --> 27:12.542
'Cause... [sighs]

27:14.500 --> 27:16.708
Well, culinary school
wasn't really working out.

27:20.917 --> 27:22.167
What does that mean?

27:23.000 --> 27:24.250
I dropped out.

27:25.500 --> 27:28.875
But don't worry. I, I have a new job.
I work at a café.

27:28.875 --> 27:30.167
And-- And I <i>love</i> it.

27:30.167 --> 27:33.083
And I actually get to paint
on my off hours,

27:33.083 --> 27:35.750
and I'm learning way more
than I learned in culinary school.

27:35.750 --> 27:36.750
Like what?

27:38.958 --> 27:43.250
Like w-waiting tables
and working the register,

27:43.250 --> 27:46.333
and-and-and learning the menu, and--

27:46.333 --> 27:51.958
And it's not just any café,
it's-- it's run by Haruto Kai.

27:51.958 --> 27:54.458
He's a very important pastry chef.

27:54.458 --> 27:56.833
Hm. Good for Mr. Kai.

27:57.333 --> 27:59.958
But what does that mean for you, Benny?

28:00.958 --> 28:05.208
W-Well, it means
I get hands-on experience and research

28:06.667 --> 28:11.375
for... when I open
my own concept café one day.

28:13.000 --> 28:15.375
It's gonna have music and art,

28:16.042 --> 28:20.375
kinda like a, um,
cultural space with dessert.

28:20.708 --> 28:21.750
[both chuckle]

28:22.500 --> 28:24.500
I wanna serve your black cake, Ma.

28:25.583 --> 28:27.583
BERT:
You-- You left school,

28:29.083 --> 28:30.458
two schools,

28:30.458 --> 28:33.208
on which I have
wasted thousands of dollars

28:33.208 --> 28:35.667
so that you can be a waitress as <i>research?</i>

28:35.667 --> 28:36.917
BENNY:
School is not for me.

28:36.917 --> 28:39.042
And there are a lot of people
in the restaurant business

28:39.042 --> 28:40.833
without a formal education.

28:40.833 --> 28:42.750
Those people are rich,

28:43.250 --> 28:44.250
and you are not.

28:44.750 --> 28:47.917
That's your problem,
you're not the one funding your failures.

28:49.667 --> 28:50.500
Oh.

28:52.333 --> 28:54.000
Is-Is-Is that all I am now?

28:54.000 --> 28:56.542
A s-series of failures?

28:56.542 --> 28:58.875
That's not how we feel.

28:58.875 --> 29:01.458
Yeah, well,
that is how you <i>make</i> me feel.

29:05.042 --> 29:06.833
When I was a little girl,

29:06.833 --> 29:10.083
you and Dad, you told me
that I could be <i>anything</i> I wanted to be.

29:10.083 --> 29:13.500
And when I told you
that I wanted to be an artist,

29:14.083 --> 29:19.792
you <i>constantly</i> invalidated
my need to explore and think and create,

29:19.792 --> 29:21.875
and then you <i>force</i> me to go to college

29:21.875 --> 29:24.667
because that's what you think
makes somebody successful!

29:24.667 --> 29:26.250
How dare you?

29:26.250 --> 29:28.208
After all we done for you!

29:28.208 --> 29:30.708
Oh, y-y-you-- You flip-flop your schools,

29:30.708 --> 29:34.042
your jobs, your apartment,
your hair, your men!

29:34.542 --> 29:35.958
And now apparently women.

29:39.792 --> 29:41.167
[softly] There it is.

29:42.000 --> 29:44.417
Ben, this isn't about--

29:44.417 --> 29:46.917
No, don't try to clean up Dad's mess.

29:46.917 --> 29:48.917
Byron, that's what he feels.

29:50.000 --> 29:52.417
He was lying when he said,
"Bring your girlfriend.

29:53.208 --> 29:56.167
The more the merrier!
Some of our <i>best</i> friends are that way."

29:56.167 --> 29:57.083
It's such bullshit!

29:57.083 --> 29:59.458
And what about you, Ma?
Were you lying too?

29:59.458 --> 30:01.000
Do not talk to your mother like that!

30:04.000 --> 30:08.083
You know, we tried to support you
when you dropped this bomb on us,

30:09.083 --> 30:12.292
just like we've been supportive of you
your entire life.

30:13.708 --> 30:15.792
But clearly, we gave you too much freedom,

30:17.125 --> 30:18.625
too many choices,

30:18.625 --> 30:22.500
because you can't even pick something
and stick with it!

30:22.500 --> 30:26.417
♪ dramatic music playing ♪

30:28.667 --> 30:31.667
♪

30:46.542 --> 30:49.375
I'm so sorry you had to go through that.

30:49.375 --> 30:52.417
But... things will calm down,
just-- just give it a few days.

30:52.417 --> 30:54.208
You shouldn't have pushed me to do this.

30:54.208 --> 30:55.042
Pushed you?

30:55.042 --> 30:57.458
If you weren't so hell-bent
on meeting my family,

30:57.458 --> 30:59.500
I wouldn't have <i>had</i> to go through this.

30:59.500 --> 31:01.625
And with a <i>fucking</i> audience, no less.

31:01.625 --> 31:04.083
I didn't insist on anything,
you know that.

31:04.083 --> 31:05.625
This isn't about me.

31:06.250 --> 31:08.500
You've been keeping
so many secrets from them.

31:09.000 --> 31:10.167
This is about you.

31:10.167 --> 31:11.417
You know what, Joanie?

31:12.125 --> 31:13.458
I get enough shit from them.

31:13.458 --> 31:14.958
I don't need any more judgment.

31:16.083 --> 31:17.250
So let's just end this.

31:19.375 --> 31:22.083
♪

31:24.750 --> 31:25.750
Benny?

31:30.042 --> 31:31.542
[tires squealing]

31:34.667 --> 31:37.083
[ambient street noise]

31:38.792 --> 31:40.792
[phone ringing]

31:50.083 --> 31:52.083
[distant siren wails]

31:56.625 --> 31:58.625
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

32:06.750 --> 32:07.958
[phone chimes]

32:10.167 --> 32:12.000
ELEANOR [on voice mail]:
<i>Benedetta, please come home.</i>

32:12.000 --> 32:15.042
<i>I know you're still upset
about last Thanksgiving,</i>

32:15.042 --> 32:16.708
<i>but we can talk--</i>
[clicks message off]

32:22.333 --> 32:25.333
♪ house music playing ♪
[indistinct chatter]

32:31.500 --> 32:32.458
[Benny sighs]

32:35.208 --> 32:36.625
It's pretty magical, right?

32:38.125 --> 32:40.417
Watching people discover your art.

32:40.417 --> 32:43.417
Wow, Mr. Dwyer. Hi.

32:43.417 --> 32:45.167
Steve. Please.

32:45.167 --> 32:47.667
- Are all the judges attending tonight?
- Mm-hmm.

32:48.417 --> 32:49.958
I have to tell you,

32:49.958 --> 32:54.292
I thought your light installation
at the Tate Modern was... incredible.

32:54.292 --> 32:57.333
- Were you in London when it opened?
- Uh, no. But I read about it.

32:59.042 --> 33:00.542
Tell me about your piece.

33:02.208 --> 33:06.250
Well... we're in the middle
of a cultural reckoning,

33:06.250 --> 33:09.500
one that transcends gender and race.

33:09.500 --> 33:12.958
So I tried to capture
some of that collective rage

33:12.958 --> 33:16.417
through utilizing
large, buttery brush strokes

33:16.417 --> 33:18.125
and broken colors.

33:21.167 --> 33:22.167
You're gifted, Benny.

33:23.333 --> 33:24.333
I hope you know that.

33:26.000 --> 33:27.000
Thank you.

33:27.667 --> 33:30.917
Mm. Maybe one day, I'll be able
to support myself through my art

33:30.917 --> 33:32.458
instead of waitressing.

33:32.458 --> 33:33.458
Not maybe.

33:34.542 --> 33:35.625
Definitely.

33:35.625 --> 33:37.208
With a little guidance,

33:37.208 --> 33:38.958
maybe as my apprentice,

33:40.583 --> 33:42.500
I think you could be quite successful.

33:42.500 --> 33:44.375
You offer apprenticeships?

33:44.375 --> 33:50.042
I think it's my responsibility
to make space for up-and-coming artists.

33:50.625 --> 33:51.750
Would you be interested?

33:51.750 --> 33:53.667
Absolutely!
[Steve chuckles]

33:53.667 --> 33:55.750
Well, I-- It-- It'd be an honor.

33:56.500 --> 33:58.375
I'll be honored to help.

34:00.417 --> 34:02.833
Maybe we could get a bit of press for you.

34:03.333 --> 34:05.833
I think your work
is exactly the sort of stuff

34:05.833 --> 34:09.375
that... that <i>Frieze</i> would love to feature.

34:09.917 --> 34:11.792
Uh, if my mom read about me

34:11.792 --> 34:14.917
in some fancy art review magazine
like <i>Frieze,</i>

34:14.917 --> 34:16.542
she would lose her shit.

34:16.542 --> 34:17.875
Oh, rightfully so.

34:17.875 --> 34:19.542
[chuckles] Thank you.

34:20.833 --> 34:22.833
[both chuckling]

34:23.833 --> 34:27.042
STEVE: <i>No one is doing
what Benny is doing with light,</i>

34:27.042 --> 34:30.042
and even some assemblage,
which is new to her.

34:30.708 --> 34:33.000
Oh, I inspired her to try it, and now...

34:33.000 --> 34:34.542
[Benny chuckles]
- ...she's hooked.

34:34.542 --> 34:35.458
[Benny and Steve laugh]

34:35.833 --> 34:38.833
Your piece at our art gallery showcase
was so powerful.

34:38.833 --> 34:40.542
Are you planning to exhibit again?

34:41.042 --> 34:43.583
Well, Helena, we haven't approached
any other galleries as yet,

34:43.583 --> 34:46.875
but... you will see her in <i>Frieze.</i>

34:46.875 --> 34:48.042
- She will?
- Mm-hmm.

34:48.042 --> 34:50.000
I was speaking to the editor
just this morning.

34:51.083 --> 34:52.083
Thank you.

34:54.375 --> 34:56.083
You should see her latest piece.

34:56.083 --> 34:57.333
Who'd like a little peek?

34:57.333 --> 34:59.500
Uh-- Wait, wait.
I don't think it's ready.

34:59.500 --> 35:00.708
STEVE:
Don't do that, Benny.

35:01.583 --> 35:03.000
Take pride in your talent.

35:06.792 --> 35:08.875
HELENA:
He's taken a real interest in you.

35:08.875 --> 35:10.042
Don't squander it.

35:12.750 --> 35:14.042
BENNY:
<i>Tonight was perfect.</i>

35:15.542 --> 35:17.833
It has been a long time since I felt,

35:17.833 --> 35:21.667
[exhales] I don't know,
supported or encouraged.

35:23.083 --> 35:24.083
Thank you.

35:24.083 --> 35:26.292
The pleasure has been <i>all</i> mine.

35:28.625 --> 35:30.333
But I sense there's

35:31.417 --> 35:32.917
more to this story.

35:34.708 --> 35:37.375
Yeah, much more.
[exhales] You have no idea.

35:38.167 --> 35:39.167
Then, tell me.

35:42.083 --> 35:43.083
Well...

35:45.000 --> 35:49.250
My parents never understood
that I wanted to make a life creating.

35:49.250 --> 35:53.167
And it's been about a year
since we had a... major fight about it.

35:54.375 --> 35:55.500
But your support

35:56.208 --> 35:57.625
makes me believe that I can,

35:58.458 --> 36:00.667
that I <i>can</i> make a life.

36:00.667 --> 36:04.125
And instead of just
telling them about it, I can

36:05.417 --> 36:07.167
show them that it's possible.

36:10.417 --> 36:12.042
You should surround yourself

36:14.083 --> 36:16.417
with people who have supported you from

36:18.500 --> 36:21.208
the very beginning, Benny.

36:21.208 --> 36:24.500
♪

36:40.458 --> 36:42.125
[Benny chuckling]

36:42.125 --> 36:45.125
STEVE:
You are so <i>stunningly</i> beautiful.

36:45.125 --> 36:47.000
Stop! [laughs]
STEVE: No.

36:49.417 --> 36:50.417
I'm gonna sculpt you.

36:52.083 --> 36:53.167
I'm gonna sculpt you,

36:54.417 --> 36:56.167
and you'll paint the finished sculpture.

36:58.833 --> 37:02.375
You want to collaborate
by sculpting <i>my</i> body?

37:02.375 --> 37:04.583
Yeah. Think of it as part portrait,

37:05.333 --> 37:07.042
part self-portrait.

37:09.375 --> 37:11.042
The lens through which I see you,

37:11.542 --> 37:15.208
overlapping with
the lens through which you see yourself.

37:17.542 --> 37:20.292
And how do you see me?

37:20.292 --> 37:21.500
As a goddess.

37:29.000 --> 37:30.042
[Benny chuckles]
- Wait there.

37:32.000 --> 37:32.833
[Steve clears throat]

37:38.000 --> 37:39.500
Have you ever worn your hair
any other way?

37:40.375 --> 37:41.542
Like how?

37:43.500 --> 37:44.500
STEVE:
I don't know, um,

37:46.292 --> 37:47.292
more feminine.

37:49.292 --> 37:52.292
♪ upbeat music playing ♪

37:55.667 --> 37:58.208
[indistinct conversation]

37:58.208 --> 38:00.125
Okay, look. Mm.

38:01.625 --> 38:02.625
[camera shutter clicks]

38:02.875 --> 38:03.708
Oh!

38:04.167 --> 38:05.500
Let's see.
- Look at you.

38:06.125 --> 38:07.750
- Aw! [laughs]
- Look at that! Look at your hair.

38:07.750 --> 38:09.125
It's fantastic.

38:09.125 --> 38:11.208
I forgot how much I love
coming to the theater.

38:11.208 --> 38:13.083
Oh, yeah.
We should make a habit of this.

38:13.667 --> 38:16.042
Once a month. You, me, and a movie.

38:16.042 --> 38:17.042
Mm. I love it.

38:17.042 --> 38:18.000
[both chuckling]

38:19.000 --> 38:20.000
Oh, God.

38:20.500 --> 38:21.500
Benny?

38:22.375 --> 38:24.708
Benny!
[both chuckling]

38:26.417 --> 38:28.500
Wow, look at you.

38:31.083 --> 38:35.083
You cut off your locs.
- Oh, it was time for a change.

38:35.083 --> 38:36.667
I can't believe it.

38:36.667 --> 38:38.500
You swore you were gonna
let them grow to your toes.

38:38.500 --> 38:40.417
Well, I think
she looks beautiful without them.

38:41.917 --> 38:42.917
Steve Dwyer.

38:43.542 --> 38:44.458
Joanie.

38:45.750 --> 38:48.542
I think she looks stunning
regardless of how she wears her hair.

38:49.250 --> 38:51.000
How's things with your family?

38:51.000 --> 38:53.750
It's been, what,
two years since that Thanksgiving.

38:53.750 --> 38:55.000
Did they come around?

38:55.875 --> 38:56.833
They didn't.

38:57.333 --> 38:58.958
I'm sure they're fine.

39:02.583 --> 39:04.542
Well, um,
I don't wanna miss the trailers.

39:05.042 --> 39:07.375
[chuckles] Yeah.
JOANIE: But I'm rooting for you
and your family.

39:09.208 --> 39:12.000
Life is too short
to hold on to grudges, you know?

39:15.167 --> 39:16.750
It's good seeing you, Benny.

39:17.250 --> 39:18.500
Take care of yourself.

39:18.500 --> 39:19.500
You too.

39:22.042 --> 39:23.042
Come on.

39:23.625 --> 39:25.875
Let's get the hell outta here.
- Wait, what's wrong?

39:26.708 --> 39:29.750
Have you any idea
how fucking humiliating that was?

39:30.417 --> 39:32.833
The way you just stood there
gaping like an idiot!

39:33.500 --> 39:35.333
You didn't even introduce me!

39:35.333 --> 39:36.333
It's like--

39:36.917 --> 39:38.417
It's like you were <i>ashamed</i> of me.

39:38.417 --> 39:39.792
What? No!

39:39.792 --> 39:41.792
I was just surprised
to see her, that's all.

39:41.792 --> 39:44.292
I have introduced you
to everyone I know.

39:45.125 --> 39:47.333
I guess when it's about your career,
you're happy to be showboated,

39:47.333 --> 39:49.458
but when it comes
to introducing me to your friends--

39:49.458 --> 39:52.917
Baby, I am sorry.
I did not mean to make you feel any--

39:52.917 --> 39:54.417
You still have feelings for her,
don't you?

39:54.417 --> 39:56.958
I don't. I'm with <i>you.</i>

39:56.958 --> 39:58.583
I love you--
- Come on, Benny!

39:58.583 --> 40:00.667
Just admit it. It's so <i>fucking</i> obvious.

40:00.667 --> 40:02.500
You're still in love with her!
- I am not!

40:02.500 --> 40:05.000
Steven, you are acting
like a <i>fucking</i> child!

40:05.500 --> 40:06.500
[Benny yelps]
[mirror shatters]

40:06.500 --> 40:09.500
♪ tense music playing ♪

40:12.000 --> 40:13.667
[Benny panting]

40:13.667 --> 40:14.500
[grunts]

40:17.958 --> 40:19.208
[heavy breaths]

40:19.625 --> 40:22.125
[panting]

40:30.667 --> 40:33.667
♪ soft music playing ♪

40:35.250 --> 40:36.250
[igniter clicking]

40:37.750 --> 40:39.750
♪

40:49.917 --> 40:50.792
[rice clatters]

40:57.417 --> 40:59.417
[knocking on door]

41:15.042 --> 41:16.042
[sighs]

41:21.958 --> 41:22.958
You're ignoring me.

41:24.500 --> 41:25.833
And do you blame me?

41:27.375 --> 41:30.792
STEVE: You won't answer my calls
or... text me back,

41:30.792 --> 41:32.750
so I came to apologize in person.

41:36.083 --> 41:37.917
Apologize for what?

41:40.792 --> 41:42.083
I need you to say it.

41:45.583 --> 41:46.792
For losing my temper.

41:49.292 --> 41:54.417
And for getting so... angry
at something so fucking stupid.

41:56.250 --> 41:57.458
I disrespected you,

42:00.792 --> 42:02.792
and you do not deserve that.

42:05.958 --> 42:07.625
I've never got so upset before.

42:08.292 --> 42:09.208
[sighs]

42:09.875 --> 42:11.250
And it's only because I--

42:12.000 --> 42:13.292
I love you.

42:17.458 --> 42:18.292
[Benny sniffles]

42:18.625 --> 42:20.042
And I don't wanna lose you.

42:23.708 --> 42:24.958
I love you too.

42:27.417 --> 42:29.500
But you scared me.
- I'm so sorry.

42:32.417 --> 42:34.708
I'm so sorry. It will never happen again.

42:37.500 --> 42:38.500
I promise.

42:42.750 --> 42:44.750
[phone ringing]

42:46.458 --> 42:47.417
[groans]

42:47.417 --> 42:48.250
[Steve sighs]

42:49.083 --> 42:51.083
[phone continues ringing]

42:56.375 --> 42:57.375
Hello?

42:59.833 --> 43:01.750
Wait, what-- What's wrong?

43:04.542 --> 43:05.542
What?

43:11.125 --> 43:12.125
Of course.

43:14.917 --> 43:16.208
I'll be there, I promise.

43:16.792 --> 43:17.792
STEVE:
What's going on?

43:22.542 --> 43:23.542
What is it?

43:28.167 --> 43:29.333
My dad died.

43:35.667 --> 43:37.583
I ghosted him for two years.

43:38.583 --> 43:41.417
I thought that
I was teaching him some lesson,

43:41.417 --> 43:43.500
setting a-- setting a boundary.

43:43.500 --> 43:46.125
Why didn't I just pick up the phone
and fucking call him?

43:46.125 --> 43:48.083
[shaky breaths]

43:49.875 --> 43:50.875
Because he hurt you.

43:52.333 --> 43:53.542
We hurt each other.

43:55.083 --> 43:56.792
And I always thought
that we would figure out a way

43:56.792 --> 43:58.042
to move past it, eventually.

43:58.042 --> 44:01.083
I-I didn't-- I didn't know
that I was-- I was running out of time.

44:01.083 --> 44:03.125
You can't just forget
everything that happened

44:03.125 --> 44:04.625
and run back to your family like--

44:06.333 --> 44:08.000
Like you weren't hurt by what they did.

44:08.000 --> 44:09.000
What?

44:10.292 --> 44:11.125
What are you saying?

44:11.125 --> 44:13.333
That I--
That I shouldn't go to the funeral?

44:13.333 --> 44:14.667
They don't deserve you.

44:14.667 --> 44:16.708
I have to be there for my family.

44:18.500 --> 44:19.833
No, you don't.

44:19.833 --> 44:23.167
Look, I want to be.
Like, I've already missed so much.

44:23.167 --> 44:24.917
I can't get that time back with my dad,

44:24.917 --> 44:27.083
but maybe it's time
that I-- that I fix things with them.

44:27.083 --> 44:28.417
STEVE:
You know what's gonna happen.

44:28.417 --> 44:29.708
You'll get hurt again,

44:29.708 --> 44:32.500
and... I'll have to pick up
all the pieces again!

44:33.458 --> 44:34.500
You don't know that!

44:34.500 --> 44:36.708
Yes. Yes, I do, Benny.

44:36.708 --> 44:38.833
Because I'm the one who shows up.

44:39.458 --> 44:42.208
Steve, this is not about you.

44:42.208 --> 44:43.208
Yes, it is.

44:43.833 --> 44:45.250
Because I'm the one who takes care of you,

44:45.250 --> 44:47.250
pays your bills, supports your career.

44:48.167 --> 44:50.125
I encourage your dreams!

44:50.125 --> 44:51.667
But you don't fucking care!

44:53.375 --> 44:55.000
That is not true.

44:55.000 --> 44:57.792
This is about <i>my</i> family.

44:57.792 --> 44:59.375
<i>I'm</i> your family!

45:02.000 --> 45:03.292
I am going home,

45:04.333 --> 45:06.000
and I am going to the funeral--

45:06.000 --> 45:07.958
You just take and you take
and you take, don't you?

45:07.958 --> 45:11.125
- I do not have to listen to this.
- You're an opportunistic, selfish dyke!

45:11.125 --> 45:12.083
[thud]
[Benny gasps]

45:13.458 --> 45:14.458
Stop!

45:19.708 --> 45:22.708
♪ somber music playing ♪

45:23.375 --> 45:25.375
[phone vibrating]

45:41.208 --> 45:42.917
[phone stops vibrating]

45:49.875 --> 45:51.875
[phone resumes vibrating]

46:01.875 --> 46:04.875
♪ somber music continues playing ♪

46:10.750 --> 46:12.750
[indistinct chatter]

46:24.458 --> 46:26.958
[birds chirping]

46:35.667 --> 46:36.750
Fuck!

46:38.042 --> 46:38.875
[sniffles]

46:43.958 --> 46:46.958
♪ somber music continues playing ♪

46:58.875 --> 46:59.792
[sighs]

47:02.958 --> 47:05.375
[water running]

47:08.500 --> 47:09.375
[dog barks]

47:10.792 --> 47:11.625
[Benny sighs]

47:12.333 --> 47:13.625
Everything okay?

47:14.125 --> 47:15.792
BENNY:
By, I think you were right about Dad.

47:17.042 --> 47:19.333
I think he would've wanted
to know the truth about Scotland.

47:20.333 --> 47:21.583
He could've helped Mom through it.

47:22.250 --> 47:26.208
And maybe without the stress
of all these secrets weighing on her,

47:27.167 --> 47:28.833
maybe she'd still be here.

47:32.792 --> 47:34.208
I don't wanna end up like that.

47:43.125 --> 47:44.458
I came to Dad's funeral,

47:45.833 --> 47:47.167
but I never got out of my car.

47:48.125 --> 47:52.500
I couldn't face you or Mom
with my face all... bruised and swollen.

47:53.375 --> 47:55.375
My ex-boyfriend, Steve,

47:56.208 --> 47:57.292
he had hit me.

47:59.667 --> 48:00.667
And it was bad.

48:01.708 --> 48:02.958
It was really bad.

48:03.625 --> 48:06.667
And I wanted to call you,
and I wanted to call Ma or the cops,

48:06.667 --> 48:07.917
but I was just afraid.

48:10.458 --> 48:11.917
Like, when I lost y'all,

48:14.375 --> 48:16.208
Steve became my everything.

48:17.958 --> 48:21.000
So I was afraid that if I called you,
that you wouldn't answer,

48:22.167 --> 48:23.333
or worse,

48:23.333 --> 48:26.125
that you would and you'd just reject me.

48:27.792 --> 48:28.792
Reject you?

48:29.833 --> 48:30.833
No.

48:32.125 --> 48:34.958
If you had called,
we would've brought you home.

48:35.583 --> 48:38.833
I couldn't bear the thought
of disappointing everybody again.

48:38.833 --> 48:39.833
Listen.

48:41.792 --> 48:43.208
I am proud of you.

48:44.708 --> 48:47.750
You got that piece of shit, Steve,
out of your life.

48:48.833 --> 48:52.083
I'm sorry
that I couldn't be there for you.

48:53.667 --> 48:55.083
I should've had your back.

48:56.125 --> 48:57.875
And I should've had your back.

48:59.708 --> 49:03.917
You went through Dad's death,
his funeral, and Mom,

49:03.917 --> 49:04.917
on your own.

49:06.583 --> 49:09.125
I needed you
just as much as you needed me.

49:10.000 --> 49:13.458
And I'm so sorry
that I just couldn't realize-- I'm so--

49:15.542 --> 49:16.583
[Benny sobs]

49:16.583 --> 49:17.583
I know.

49:20.167 --> 49:21.292
I know that now.

49:21.750 --> 49:22.667
[Benny cries]

49:24.625 --> 49:25.833
ELEANOR:
<i>B and B,</i>

49:27.042 --> 49:31.125
<i>your father's funeral
was the death of two dreams,</i>

49:31.125 --> 49:33.958
<i>that Bert and I would grow old together</i>

49:33.958 --> 49:39.417
<i>and that our family would, one day,
be made whole again by Benny's return.</i>

49:40.458 --> 49:44.417
<i>I have to believe that we would've
found our way back to each other</i>

49:44.417 --> 49:47.167
<i>if time had been on our side.</i>

49:48.125 --> 49:50.458
<i>That is why, my sweet girl,</i>

49:51.167 --> 49:53.292
<i>I hope you absolve yourself</i>

49:53.292 --> 49:56.458
<i>of whatever guilt you feel
about missing the funeral.</i>

49:57.417 --> 50:01.375
<i>Some promises are hard to keep.</i>

50:03.000 --> 50:06.667
B and B, I'm sharing this with you

50:06.667 --> 50:11.583
because I now know how important it is
to lean on those you love.

50:14.917 --> 50:18.500
Love brings the light

50:20.000 --> 50:23.542
that will guide you
out of your darkest moments.

50:24.250 --> 50:28.000
♪ soft music playing ♪

50:36.542 --> 50:39.875
<i>Reuniting with your father was a miracle.</i>

50:39.875 --> 50:42.750
[Bert humming]

50:43.250 --> 50:44.125
[Bert chuckles]

50:44.500 --> 50:46.500
♪

50:51.708 --> 50:55.167
[indistinct chatter on TV]
[both laughing]

51:00.958 --> 51:04.542
ELEANOR:
<i>The life we made for ourselves,
our home, our family,</i>

51:05.917 --> 51:07.417
<i>our sweet baby boy</i>

51:08.542 --> 51:09.542
<i>and girl</i>

51:11.125 --> 51:14.708
<i>were miracles on top of miracles.</i>

51:17.750 --> 51:21.458
♪

51:25.667 --> 51:26.667
Bert?

51:32.917 --> 51:33.917
Bert?

51:48.000 --> 51:49.292
[gasps] Oh, God.

51:52.292 --> 51:54.000
[gasps]

51:54.583 --> 51:58.833
[crying] Ohhh, my sweet Gibbs.

52:00.792 --> 52:02.208
[sobbing]

52:08.250 --> 52:11.792
I promised myself I would take
all of this with me to my grave.

52:14.625 --> 52:18.958
I didn't want to burden you, my miracles,

52:19.917 --> 52:21.167
with the weight of it.

52:24.750 --> 52:26.208
But in doing that,

52:26.208 --> 52:31.417
I lost a piece of myself, I think.

52:33.750 --> 52:37.125
Even now, it feels like... I'm drowning.

52:39.292 --> 52:40.625
[sharp inhale and exhale]

52:42.500 --> 52:45.792
I wish I'd had the courage
to share the truth with you sooner

52:45.792 --> 52:48.708
because that's what
all three of my children deserve.

52:54.708 --> 52:56.125
You heard me correctly.

52:56.125 --> 52:58.750
♪ mysterious music playing ♪

53:00.667 --> 53:01.750
[sharp inhale and exhale]

53:03.458 --> 53:04.458
A secret

53:06.208 --> 53:08.792
I couldn't bring myself
to even share with your father,

53:08.792 --> 53:11.208
I'm now telling you.

53:14.208 --> 53:15.208
B and B,

53:18.208 --> 53:19.417
you have a sister.

53:19.875 --> 53:21.875
♪ dramatic crescendo ♪
